67 Old fame calls them blind in the world;
68 the people are greedy, envious and proud:
69 from their customs make that you restrain yourself.

79 “If all my request were full,” 80 I answered to him, “you would not yet be 81 placed in exile from the human race;
82 because it is fixed in my mind, and now it saddens me, 83 the dear and good paternal image of you 84 when, hour by hour in the world,
85 you taught me how man makes himself eternal: 86 and as much as I have it in degree, while I live 87 it is necessary that it be chosen in my language.”

94 Such a speech is not new to my ears;
95 therefore let Fortune turn her wheel
96 as it pleases her, and the peasant his hoe.

97 My master then on the cheek
98 right turned back and looked at me;
99 then he said: “Listen well who takes note.”

103 And he to me: “To know of someone is good;
104 of the others it would be laudable to be silent,
105 because the time would be short for so much sound.”
